Introduction¶

Dataset Source¶

The data source which was used in this project is the Car Detail from Car Dekho which was sourced from Kaggle (Kaggle. (2019). Kaggle: Your Home for Data Science. Kaggle.com.). This dataset (dataset link) contains the prices of 4340 used cars that were sold.

Dataset Details¶

This dataset is about the prices of used cars that were sold and their data was collected by CarDekho, an Indian website that is primarily used for buying and selling cars. It dataset contains information about each car that was sold such as the name of the car, the year of manufacture, the kilometres driven, the fuel the car uses, the seller type, the transmission of the car, the type of owner selling the car and most importantly, the price which the car was sold at. This information is adequate to construct a predictive model of used car selling prices as a regressive problem.

This dataset has 8 features and 4340 observations.

Response Variable¶

In this project, the response variable will be the selling price of the car sold in Indian Rupees. This selling price of the car sold in Indian Rupees will be predicted on the basis of the explanatory variables such as the number of kilometers that the car has driven, the year of manufacture of the car, the transmission and the other features that were also described in the table above.

Goals and Objectives¶

The car market in India has been growing for the last few decades. In particular, the used car market in India has been said to grow at a compounded annual growth rate of 11%, and has been predicted to reach sales of up to 8.3 million by the financial year of 2026. In relation to this, online car marketplaces, one being CarDekho as presented in this project, have become highly popularised. Therefore, by analysing the data collected from CarDekho through a model that can predict a used cars selling price can help greatly in the real world. Car dealerships as well as individuals who want to sell their car(s) or may want to sell them sometime in the future can use the predicted selling prices to help them with their financial planning such as factoring in the predicted amount of money that they would receive from selling their car(s). Furthermore, individuals may use the predicted data to help them sell their car at the right price and avoid being underpaid for their car.

The objective of this project is to predict the selling price of used cars based on the information about the car such as the make, the number of kilometers it was driven when it was sold, the transmission of the car and so on. This will ultimately aid car dealerships as well as individuals who want to sell their used car(s).

As seen above, the dataset as 4340 rows, so in this project all 4340 sales of used cars will be used to make predictions.

However, the name column contains the make of the car as well the model of the car, however, in order to clean this data since there might be naming errors within the format of the model part of the names attribute, the model part will be dropped and only the name of the manufacturer of the car will remain so that accurate modeling may be conducted and car manufacturers, car dealerships and individuals may see the general results of the selling price of each car brand rather than the car brand as well as it's specific model.

The code below splits the name attribute of the cars dataframe so that only the brand of the car is stored and the model of the car is discarded.

In [8]:
cars_df['name'] = cars_df.name.str.split().str.get(0)

From the scatterplot above, most of the used cars that were sold which had a newer year of manufacture had were owned by the first owner, as the year of manufacture of the car decreased, that is, the car was manufactured a longer time ago, the number of owners of the car were increased to 2, 3, and finally 4 or more owners. This could be logically explained because older cars have spent more time in the world, so on that basis, they would have had more owners as they were sold on to others. From the analysis of this scatterplot however, a key observation can be made, that is, as the number of owners of the certain car increased, the selling price of the used car tended to decrease. Because most of the cars that only had a first owner had a higher selling price than the rest of the cars which had were owned by more people than the first owner.

Summary and Conclusions¶

This project was aimed to analyse the data from the popular Indian online car marketplace named CarDekho which consisted of the sales of 4340 used cars. The data collected consisted of the attributes of each car sold as listed in the following; the name of car brand, the year of manufacture of the car, the number of kilometers driven by the car at the point of sale, the fuel which the car uses, the seller type of the car, the transmission, the number of previous owners of the car (including seller) and finally the selling price of the car. The aim of the phase 1 of the project was to study the factors that affected the selling price of used cars and in turn, make a prediction for the selling price of used cars.

From this analysis, it was found that a correlation exits between the number of kilometers driven and the selling price of the car. The correlation was that as the number of kilometers driven of the car increased, the selling price of the car tended to decrease. Furthermore, it was also discovered that as the year of manufacture of the car increased, that is, the car was manufactured more recently, the selling price of the car had increased as well. This reflected a correlation between these two attributes, however, to further study this finding, this data was analysed further by also using the attributes; the number of previous owners and transmission of the car. As stated previously, the selling price of the car tended to decrease as the number of kilometers driven increased, however, it was also found that as the number of kilometers driven by the car was lower, the number of previous owners of the car was also lower, this could be said that the affect of the selling price of the car to be lower was possibly caused by the reduced number of previous owners and not the year of manufacture of the car. Furthermore, in relation to the same two attributes, the year of manufacture of the car and the selling price of the car, another attribute, the transmission of the car, could have been a factor in this correlation. Regardless of the year of manufacture of the car, the selling price of the cars with an automatic transmission tended to be higher than the cars with a manual transmission. However, most of the cars with an automatic transmission generally had a much more recent manufacture year than the cars with a manual transmission.

Ultimately, it was found that used cars that had a higher selling price generally had a much more recent year of manufacture, were driven a lower number of kilometers, had a lower number of previous owners and had an automatic transmission.

Conclusively, further analysis will be taken based on these results to further dissect the outward trends that were observed from phase 1 of this project and further commentary on underlying factors will be explored in phase 2 of this project.
